The defendant Edward L Henderson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Cocaine/Coca(2nd+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(c).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by the parties. 

AS TO COUNT :1
Court ordered defendant to serve 10 MONTHS in the House of Correction concurrent to case 15CF4294 and consecutive to any other sentence;release for inmate work assignments within the House of Correction, The Day Reporting Center; with credit for 56 days time served (3/8/16 & 3/9/16) and (4/15/16-6/7/16). Court notes a strong objection to electronic monitoring. 

- Fine is set at ZERO.
- Pay all mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge, BY 07/01/2017. Any remaining balance will become immediately due or civil judgment to be entered. 
- Provide DNA sample, if not already done. 
- Drivers license suspension is not imposed.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.

Defendant Edward L Henderson in court with attorney Kiley Beth Zellner.  Defendant Edward L Henderson in custody.  Chad Wozniak appeared for the State of Wisconsin./LNR   

Plea hearing proceeded. Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by defense counsel and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:

The defendant was advised of his Constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Jury Instructions and Addendum to Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible. 

Case proceeded to sentencing hearing.
